text: i'm fine. these issues have been brought up because they need to be addressed and only because improvements need to be made. before writing it all out i've always been quiet and well, mouse. i understand that's not ever going to be the same. i'd like to hold onto the shred of humanity i have left. not get badgered in good or bad ways. grateful for what i have in life, for surviving. for the few people who talk to me like a person, that's really important. for homey golden little pony boy who's been holding me down through the adventure, all wild and free like. i'm not the face of rape, my name is kelsey and it's be nice if i can continue to grow rather than being put back there. haven't done that yet, won't do it now, just feel like that more than necessary. eminem and xzibit dont approach me describes it well.  #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #toomuchclout #nomanhasclaimonmylife #nojusticenopeace

text:
we ache for connection.  we ache for truth and to be seen.  and heard. 
a couple of months ago i was in north carolina in an uber and talking to the driver, he said that he’d been working for days and no one had engaged in a conversation. 
just in talking to him and asking about his life realized how often i disappear into the little white box in front of me.  at first books were an introverts best friend, and now the phone. 
real connection, where we meet eyes and match heartbeats is more and more rare- i have my phone up for a week during retreat a couple of weeks ago.  and then i noticed just how little real conversation was happening.  when i got the phone back it didn’t take long for me to get right back in.  so now, putting the phone down is a practice.  connecting is a practice.  however awkward for me it’s just as important as my meditation or morning dance party. 
fuck it.  the message can wait, the text will get sent.  call it connection or co-regulating it heart meeting- let’s connect irl. 
i’ll start with eye contact, sister.  then let’s tell the truth.  and dance.  will you meet me?

text: (2/4) in undergrad, there are a whole bunch of personalities put together in a small place. and it was then that i realized i needed to find my own identity. but college was a life-changingly difficult time for me. without going into all the details, i didn’t receive proper and appropriate counseling and help for dealing with a toxic relationship, i lost touch with friends because of it, and i struggled to keep up with classes. furthermore, sophomore year i lost my grandmother, and junior year i lost 3 classmates in a car accident. i became so concerned for my personal safety that at one point, i left in the middle of the night. when the #metoo movement broke out shortly after i left, i took comfort in seeing my school struggling to right the wrongs of their past.

text:
why the camellia in my mother’s garden is a badass
it was thanksgiving day and it was cold. 
all the other flowers were dead and gone, wimped out with the first frost. 
but not this showstopper. 
not only was this bright pink camellia in my mother’s garden gorgeous in spite of the cold, she was gorgeous because of it. 
camellias need winter. 
they need the cold to strut their stuff. 
if the bright pink camellia in my mother’s garden could talk, i think she’d flip her hair back and share the secret of how to find your mojo in the middle of a cold, dead season. 
and i think she’d leave us with this quote by albert camus: “in the midst of winter, i finally learned that there was within me an invincible summer.”
sisters—be a camellia. 
use the tough stuff, the abuse, the abandonment, the harsh words, the criticism, the  negativity, all the winter life throws at us, and bloom, dangitall. 
winter can kill you if you let it. 
but it can also make you a badass. 
i choose in the midst of winter, to find my invincible summer. 
how bout you? 
#camellias #inthemidstofwinter #albertcamus #badasswomen #bloomwhereyouareplanted #overcome #trauma #findyourself #findyourmuchness #metoo #metoomovement #lovewins

why the camellia in my mother’s garden is a badass
it was thanksgiving day and it was cold. 
all the other flowers were dead and gone, wimped out with the first frost. 
but not this showstopper. 
not only was this bright pink camellia in my mother’s garden gorgeous in spite of the cold, she was gorgeous because of it. 
camellias need winter. 
they need the cold to strut their stuff. 
if the bright pink camellia in my mother’s garden could talk, i think she’d flip her hair back and share the secret of how to find your mojo in the middle of a cold, dead season. 
and i think she’d leave us with this quote by albe camus: “in the midst of winter, i finally learned that there was within me an invincible summer.”
sisters—be a camellia. 
use the tough stuff, the abuse, the abandonment, the harsh words, the criticism, the  negativity, all the winter life throws at us, and bloom, dangitall. 
winter can kill you if you let it. 
but it can also make you a badass. 
i choose in the midst of winter, to find my invincible summer. 
how bout you?

text:
lo que pasó el martes en multiteatro merece una celebración. es el resultado de años de militancia, puesta en común de prácticas y una escucha atenta del feminismo a las mujeres y disidencias que padecen las violencias machistas. también es el dolor que circula cuando sabemos que todas fuimos abusadas, de una u otra manera, y que al mismo tiempo que podemos decirlo vemos a los varones pararse de manos y replegarse en una actitud tribal: “yo nunca le pegué a nadie” parecen decir, o dicen de hecho.

de ese conjunto de experiencias de activismo, puesta de cuerpos en la calle y palabras para nombrar lo que no tiene nombre se gestó ni una menos, la pelea por el aborto legal y los paros de mujeres que se hicieron en este país e irradiaron su potencia a toda latinoamérica, al mundo.

la insistencia con apelar al #metoo como hashtag explicativo y protector de una causa de la que podemos dar cátedra, molesta e incomoda, porque no hay #metoo argentino, hay un movimiento con una historia propia, que peleó por tomar la palabra aun cuando ésta estaba prohibida, y pienso en nuestras desaparecidas, en las madres y abuelas con su ritual de ronda y en las militantes que se hicieron en los ochenta con la propia experiencia y ese ruido constante a injusticia que recae sobre las identidades mujer, lesbiana, trans, travesti.

text: holiday classic or creepy come-on? a cultural debate has erupted over “baby, it’s cold outside,” the 1944 song by frank loesser (pictured with his wife, with whom he’d perform the song), after some radio stations decided to pull it over complaints from listeners. the song — a holiday classic despite no mention of any holiday — tells the story of a cold evening with a man and woman in which the man tries to convince the woman to stay (“baby, it’s cold outside”) and she repeatedly protests. “i think the song has always been creepy,” said lydia liza, a singer-songwriter. “but we didn’t have the words to explain why.” 📸: anthony camerano/associated press ❄️ what songs have you revisted in the light of #metoo?

text:
ever thought about volunteering?⠀
dorset rape crisis support centre (drcsc) are looking for #helpline #volunteers, as well as events volunteers to help with #theconsenttent and #fundraising. ⠀
if you are interested in volunteering please email info@dorsetrapecrisis.org.⠀
drcsc provides a comprehensive induction training programme for anyone wishing to volunteer on the telephone helpline. ⠀
on completion of the induction training you will be required to cover the helpline for a minimum of 2 x 2 hour sessions per month and attend the volunteer support group meeting held in the evening every third monday of the month.⠀

text:
😡y si, hay gente quienes dicen que 9 años es muy tarde para denunciarlo. ¿qué tipo de mente sucia e infantil puede pensar que una actriz quiere llamar la atención con una violación? ¡no señores! creo que todas las mujeres nos sentimos en algún momento avergonzadas solo al escuchar acosos en las calles y decir que querer llamar la atención ¿con una violación? ¿para ser más famosa? ¿para que hablen de ella? ¿para que no se quede en el olvido? ¿ella se le insinuo? ..ese tipo de comentarios me enferman y de por si he escuchado en toda mi vida mucho de eso por parte de hombres e incluso de mujeres a quienes les parece que por ser haber nacido mujer debes evitar "provocar a los hombres".
el muy enfermo le dijo "...mira como me pones..." ahora nosotras te decimos:¡¡¡ mira como nos ponemos!!!
........................................................................ 😡and yes, there are people who say that 9 years is too late to report it. what kind of dirty, childish mind may think that an actress wants to get attention with a sexual violation? no, people! i think that all the women in our life have felt ashamed to hear street harassment and some say: she wants to get attention? with a violation? she wants to be more famous? she wants that the people talk about her?  she insinuated him? ..this type of comments make me sick and yes! i have heard in my life a lot of this kind of commentaries from men and women who think that being born a woman should avoid "incite men." he said her: "... look at how hard i get ..." now we are telling you: look at how hard we get!!! #miracomonosponemos

text:
“a todas mis amigas (mujeres) conservadores que se han burlado o quejado sobre la marcha de las mujeres (women’s march) les recuerdo que:⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- cada vez que vas a votar para elegir tu candidato preferido, lo estás haciendo porque alguna vez las mujeres marcharon.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- cada vez que compras tus anticonceptivos para así poder planificar cuál es el mejor momento para tener una familia (o cuántos hijos querés tener), lo estás haciendo porque alguna vez las mujeres marcharon.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- cada vez que vas a trabajar fuera de casa para proveer para vos y tu familia, lo estás haciendo porque alguna vez las mujeres marcharon.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- cada vez que abres tu cuenta de banco, compras propiedades o hacés una decisión financiera independiente, lo estás haciendo porque alguna vez las mujeres marcharon.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
las cosas que tienes hoy son el producto de una protesta, una inconformidad social, activismo y resistencia. incluso hasta la mujer más anti-feminista del siglo xxi, vive en la sombra de las mujeres activistas que estuvieron dispuestas a luchar por generaciones que nunca iban a llegar a conocer”.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
efecto #metoo argentino: hay 9 denuncias telefónicas por hora de abusos sexuales
nueve llamadas por hora. esa es la frecuencia que registró este miércoles la línea telefónica en la que el ministerio de justicia y derechos humanos de la nación recibe consultas y denuncias de abuso sexual infantil. entre su promedio diario de 16 casos y los 214 que hubo este miércoles el crecimiento de las consultas fue del 1.240 por ciento.

no es casual: la denuncia penal y pública por violación que hizo la actriz thelma fardin contra juan darthés multiplicó los contactos con la línea telefónica (0800-222-1717) que depende del ministerio incluso ese mismo día, después de la conferencia de prensa en el multiteatro. hubo 55 llamadas, más del triple del promedio de 16 por día.

no es casual: la denuncia penal y pública por violación que hizo la actriz thelma fardin contra juan dahés multiplicó los contactos con la línea telefónica (0800-222-1717) que depende del ministerio incluso ese mismo día, después de la conferencia de prensa en el multiteatro. hubo 55 llamadas, más del triple del promedio de 16 por día.

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
cincuenta años después de su nacimiento, cuando movimientos como time's up o #metoo han dado eco a mujeres de todo el mundo y la lucha por los derechos de las mujeres está más que nunca en el candelero, su lectura del mundo sigue en plena vigencia. las #viñetas del genial #quino adquieren hoy una fuerza extraordinaria y nos ayudan a tomar conciencia del camino recorrido y por recorrer para conseguir la #igualdadd género.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
luego de que @merydelcerrok narrara el abuso sexual que sufrió cuando era pequeña, @baronjimena, amiga y compañera de la modelo en el “bailando por un sueño”, se mostró muy angustiada y le dedicó unas palabras. “no puedo creer. no puedo creer enterarme así, enterarme ahora, enterarme acá. te adoro amiga, eso ya lo sabes y no tengo que decir lo excelente persona que sos”, comenzó diciendo barón y añadió: “aprovecho para destacar que pasa esto. que logran que no hablemos, que nos de vergüenza. eso es lo que hacen los abusadores, hoy juan darthés dio el ejemplo. nos tratan de locas y tratan de que quedemos mal nosotras”. para finalizar dejó un mensaje para todas las mujeres que sufren o sufrieron abusos: “basta de eso. hablemos estamos todas juntas. créannos, y si no nos creen no nos importa porque estamos todas juntas y porque esto empezó para no parar”.
.

text:
photo: wagon-chapelle: a traveling russian orthodox church car⠀
⠀
the trans-siberian railway⠀
one of the remarkable elements the trans-siberian train was the wagon-chapelle, a traveling russian orthodox church. staffed by russian orthodox priests, the train travelled from station to station, making up for the shortage of local churches in siberia. it was equipped with ringing bells at the end of the skylight to summon the faithful when approaching stations.⠀
⠀
read further at https://buff.ly/2bot3ks on the history the trans-siberian railway that lily used to travel in russia, from st. petersburg to vladivostok, in the blog: the trans-siberian railway⠀

text:
the awareness on the topic of sexual violence is very essential. the former british foreign secretary, william hague, and the hollywood actress who is famous for her activism, angelina jolie, started the project aiming to bring awareness in this far-reaching issue. *
*
*

this project had a very big start and several goals were already reached. according to william hague, this project had an impact on making un pass security council resolutions on preventing sexual violence, including getting 155 nations to sign up to action on the issue at the general assembly. also, their work helped to gather young and global filmmakers to discuss the representations of sexual violence and its effects.
*
*
*

icdo supports the work of william hague and angelina jolie and stresses the importance of the project.

text:
👇🏼poem at bottom👇🏼
we are a week away from this year’s winter solstice 🥰 & i absolutely love my home and the town i live in. it was my dream to live in colorado as my chosen home someday & although i am usually antsy to leave a place after about 6 months to a year due to my constant uprooting and moving in my life, i’m still deeply in love with our little town almost 4 years into living here - and fall further each day. the love in my home from my family, the love i receive through others, and the love i practice for this self, this life, & this home has immensely contributed to this healing journey to recovery 🙏🏻 —————————————————
i bend and i bow through the frosty snow 
when sudden bits
& flittering fits
of secrets from crows 
come sweeping low 💜
📸 by me 💓 #iahsay #cptsdrecovery #cherryblossom #japanesecherryblossom #mybackyard #poetrybyme #writersofinstagram

i bend and i bow through the frosty snow 
when sudden bits
& flittering fits
of secrets from crows 
come sweeping low 💜
📸 by me 💓

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

just hours after his depaure from the trump administration became public, breitba, whose traffic and adveising have fallen significan notly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitba editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitba gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitba told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robe mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg repoed.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i have been absent from social media for a couple of weeks now. my closest friends and i went through hell for the 6 longest days when our dear friend went missing. our beautiful carla went to costa rica to celebrate her 36 birthday to never return. on november 27 she stopped responding to calls and messages, and on december 5, her family members were able to identify her body and give the world the devastating news that our beloved friend was gone. 
the security guard at the @airbnb in san jose was the beast that took her from us. he is in custody at the moment, but the investigation keeps going. 
violence against women is a devastating very real issue. and girls like her that love to travel and enjoy life, pay the highest price. 
if you want to follow up with carla’s story, you can visit the facebook page we created to share her story: finding carla.

text:
k n o w i n g ✨ is practiced by listening to my inner voice. it’s the seeing without my eyes. i’ve sharpened my intuition; heightened my senses. in seas of chaotic confusion, in the depths of darkness, i’ve developed my insight. through dedicated practice, my inner light illuminates my pathway. now, when the knowing comes, it’s impossible to deny. ✨
i don’t leave my inner child to scream: ‘something is wrong! it’s not what it seems!’ and ignore her. i listen and i believe her. if it doesn’t feel right, it’s not. if i’m sick to my stomach - it’s a familiar deceit. i’ve felt it before so i recognize and accept rather than brush it off with, ‘i must be crazy?’ - it couldn’t possibly be exactly what i feel it is, could it? it is. and i know now. knowing doesn’t make the feelings go away. pain is still pain but i allow the processing faster now. i let the illusion go. allow the lesson in. 💕
i still love fantasy delusion. i still want it to be different - this time. and i imagine i always will, until it is. but i now know, when it’s not 🙂 
the kindest thing we can offer another person, is the same kindness we can show ourselves: 
remind yourself to trust your knowing. ✨
it’s the primary practice i coach my clients on. how to recognize their inner knowing. developing personal toolkits for their process. it’s our ultimate power and we all are able to access our own potent magic this way.
✨
when we know now, what we wished we’d known then (well - which we did but denied for ages first) then we empower ourselves to make different choices. 
and that’s our only control in any situation: the choice we make. 📸 picture of me drinking coffee and knowing things 👩🏻🧙🏼‍♀️👼🏻...
.
.
.
.
.
.

text_retweet:
#repost @oraclelilith with @get_repost
・・・
at the border, while i’m getting back my passport: “have a wonderful journey cute face”

a puppy is cute. babies are cute. stuffed puppets are cute. an outfit can be cute. 
the things i think and say are not cute. my world views are not cute. my opinions and feelings are not cute. the idiosyncrasies and contradictions that make me are not cute. i’m not cute.

i am a strong, complex and powerful human being and i’m tired to be recognised only by my physical features. i feel like i want to scrub my face so hard that i will finally peel off this label.

just don’t call me cute!
❌💪🏼👸🏻
#dontcallmecute #everydaysexism #slaythepatriarchy #thisisnotacompliment #selfieholic #duckfacequeen #feministdiary #lilithhasspoken

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the company’s role on trump’s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with “judith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured self”. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanel’s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum – which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a “pre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time period”. he conceded that while cambridge analytica “exploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put out”, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: “we need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversity” in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust – and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the company’s role on trump’s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with “judith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured self”. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanel’s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum – which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a “pre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time period”. he conceded that while cambridge analytica “exploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put out”, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: “we need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversity” in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust – and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text_retweet:
please read this post by @jasonmboyce. it’s time for the industry to stop burying its head in the sand. #time4respect #repost @jasonmboyce
・・・
- i’ve stayed pretty quiet about things pertaining to my lawsuit. a lot has gone on that no one knows about that has caused pain, anxiety and bouts of depression. but after this i cannot stay silent any longer. -  @wwd interviewed bruce weber. when asked about me, he had this to say, “i hope sometime soon that we have other things to talk about”. i feel like this statement represents all of fashion in this #metoo moment. they hope that one day this will all blow over. if they ignore it and treat it as a fly in the ointment, they will come away unscathed. if any model wanted to know what the powers that be thinks about them, look no further than that statement. -

i am not a human being. i am a problem, a nuisance, an inconvenience. how dare i stand up for myself and countless other young men that have been sexually abused in the name of “artistic expression”. in another interview done by wwd, hercules mag co-owner david vivirido, when asked about sexual assault accusations said, “of course it’s not the same as someone accused of something like rape”..... let that sink in real deep. so as long as you don’t rape anybody, you have a place in fashion. this is precedent being set by people in power in such a close knit industry. controlled by a powerful few. -

so my question is, how many young men and women need to come forward for a change to happen? how many lives that have been broken due to the abuse suffered at the hands of photographers, casting directors, and agents will it take for something to be done?? -

i also hope that at some point we will have something else to talk about. because i’m sick and tired of talking about men with power and influence, preying on the vulnerable. i’m sick and tired of talking about people in a position to do something about it, standing by and doing nothing. 
truth is inevitable, and change is coming.

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the company’s role on trump’s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with “judith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured self”. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanel’s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum – which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a “pre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time period”. he conceded that while cambridge analytica “exploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put out”, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: “we need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversity” in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust – and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
dear writer girl,

your words never failed to amaze me, every time you held the pen. the ink your quill spills might not leave an everlasting splash on others but for me, it's as indelible as for the sheet.

it's been awhile since we had coffee by my balcony.
i'd look at the setting sun and try to contemplate on life and you'd be there, smiling with my t-shirt on... staring at me, capturing every particular detail which even the almighty might have missed.

i've seen you fighting with words in order to give the perfect justice to the way i kissed you, how you caressed my hair whilst i rested my head on your lap, how badly you wanted to hide yourself within my arms on seeing a cockroach while i'd be busy being grateful to the creature.

sometimes i felt, your words were too exquisite to be true but the facade was too charming to be ignored. "words do turn me on!", i know i told you when we met for the first time and it was the first time that our eyes actually met and our cheeks went red. but...was it the crave for words? or some form of mutual...rather real existence, out of your scripted world.
i know you could muse a dozen set of verse for me but was being real too difficult?

love,
not so a writer guy.

sourav dey
(@quill_and_paper)
.
.
.

text:
mercúrio em sagitário e muitas coisas acontecendo no mundo dos ~salvadores~... a lembrar: quando júpiter entrou em escorpião rolou aquele movimento #metoo onde diretores de hollywood foram denunciados por assédio. tinha tudo a ver com a sexualidade e poder. não é porque júpiter saiu de escorpião que o que emergiu volta para o fundo. não. em sagitário chegamos à luz e compreensão de muita coisa! miramos para o alto e para a libertação. mercúrio saiu do movimento retrô e ajuda mais ainda as fichas a caírem, a falar sobre nossas verdades. 5o e 7o chakras ativados, amplia a nossa capacidade de expressão e compreensão das coisas.
o que é importante pensar aqui: sagitário é um eterno buscador, de respostas, de sabedoria, de fé e às vezes fica meio fanático. atenção: tudo, tudo o que nos atrai que tem a ver com cura e salvação de alguma coisa está relacionada a nossa capacidade de apreender os ensinamentos. nosso guru interno, nossa intuição, nossa consciência que faz as conexões necessárias para nos movermos para frente, entendem? 
nada errado com buscar! nada errado (o que é certo e errado afinal?) em encontrar sua religião, seu mentor nem nada disso, desde que estejamos conscientes de que a mudança parte da gente e não de alguém que manipula a gente. atenção aos dogmatismos, amiguinhos, pensar é livre!

text:
[caption]
.
we were touched inappropriately when we didn't even know what it meant.
when we were gripped with fear that if we spoke to strangers they would take us away in their sacks,
we dared not to open our lips in front of people,
we weren't sacked,
but we were abused.
we didn't know what their intentions were. but , we just knew that they touched our body.
we were asked to send nudes when we didn't even know what they would do with it.
we were sent nudes with a long message describing the aftermath . and guess what, we didn't even know the terms.
at home , when everything was meant to be the safe . 
our relatives had other plans.
tutors had their parts too , tricking with punishments and having their share of pleasure .
and now when we look back ,we get aware of how we dealt with it in the past. 
we have forgotten the past but we remember our experiences.
we always look forward to the new day. to the new society. to a day when we would not say it out of bravery  but we would say it with our conscience within -
"we aren't afraid of men anymore."
.
follow- @words.in.symphony to read more from us.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
what should be one of the biggest takeaways of #metoo & why childhood sexual molestation & violence must be stopped:
🔸’i may not have been able to say it at the time but the actions you took then, resulted in the pain that caused me to make choices that i should not have, to live a life that i otherwise would not have, to look at the world through lenses i need not.....’
🔸there is so much more than meets the eye to the devastation that is the aftermath of sexual assault. it is not just an individual sufferance to be hushed or ignored, nor is it a grab for attention or savvy political tactic. rather, it is a societal woe and a loss of valuable life on many levels, that requires our attention.  these are at the roots of what has gone awry 🌏❤️ #conversationsthathelp

text:
8 years and till infinity.
.
people say, the most beautiful feature in oneself is their smile. but there should be a reason for smiling.
lavleen kaur @lavleen26.kaur is one such reason for my smile.
we used to travel by same school bus and this is how we became friends. and we are best-friends since then.

you know why best? not everyone deserves this best title. she deserves because she is the one who knows me-
from fighting with me to fighting for me,
from sharing tiffins to sharing the title of best-friends,
from crying for me to crying with me,
from sitting on the same bench to sitting on my lap,
from crying on my shoulders to wiping those tears with my handkerchief,
she has always been the best.

someone who has walked my ways,
who knows my everyday pain.
someone who sometimes makes me a cry baby,
who meets me after long and becomes a cry baby.
even if time itself comes to an end
i'll be there for you till eternity.
you always put me first if i need you to be there,
someone lovable like you is really rare.

i love you @lavleen26.kaur (🐂)😂 ❤️
.
tag your best friend in the comment section and show some love 💗
.
- from priyanshi @poetrybypriyanshi 
__________________________

in these times of #metoo and stories of sexual harassment, there are also women and men around us who made us feel more beautiful, more confident and powerful from both inside and out. 
if there is a person who brought some meaningful changes in your life, then let's pay a tribute to her/him right here at @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, don't we?

text:
on jubilee street
there was a girl named bee
she had a history
but she had no past
when they shut her down
the russians moved in
i’m too scared, i’m too scared
to even walk on past
she used to say
all those good people
down on jubilee street
they ought to practice what they preach
those good people
on jubilee street
and here i come up the hill
i’m pushing my wheel of love
i got love in my tummy
and a tiny little pain
and a ten ton catastrophe
on a sixty pound chain
and i’m pushing
my wheel of love up jubilee street

oh, look at me now, look at me now

the problem was
she had a little black book
and my name was written on every page
well a girl’s got to make ends meet
even down on jubilee street
i was out of place and time
and over the hill
and out of my fucking mind
on jubilee street
i ought to practice what i preach
these days i go down town
in my tie and tails
i got a foetus on a leash
i am alone now
i am beyond recriminations
the curtains are shut
the furniture has gone
i am transforming
i am vibrating
i am glowing
i am flying

look at me now

nick cave

text:
en liten dansstund mitt i vardagsbestyren...
vill dela med mig av denna låt, och egentligen hela album av magiska @robynkonichiwa som betyder väldigt mycket för mig🖤
.
albumet "robyn" släpptes waaay back in 2005 och är så före sin tid! både vad gäller musiken, men framförallt de fantastiska texterna!🙌🏻
de hade lika gärna kunnat varit skrivna i år och är så fulla av feminism, kaxighet, pepp och magi!!✨🌟✨
om ni inte lyssnat på det, gört!
.
👇🏻läs texten till denna låt, och tänk att den skrevs för över 13 år sedan! lååångt innan #metoo, instagram, kroppspositivism & feminism-rörelsena💪🏻♀️✊🏻
•••
"good girls are pretty, like all the time.
i'm just pretty some of the time.

good girls are happy and satisfied.
i won't stop asking, until i die.

i just can't deal with the rules, i can't take the pressure.
it's got me saying...
.
who's that girl? that you dream of.
who's that girl? that you think you love.
who's that girl? well i'm nothing like her.
i know there's no such girl.
i swear i can't take the pressure.
who's that girl?

good girls don't say no, or ask you why.
i wont let you love me until you really try.
good girls are sexy, like everyday.
i'm only sexy when i say it's okay.
.
//let's play a game that you've never tried.
you be the girl and i'll be the guy.
let's pretend everything has changed, and then...
would you love me any different?"
🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻 🙌🏻

text:
victoria szpunberg, emma cohen, angélica lidell, carmen resino o marta galán son algunas de las dramaturgas cuyas obras se abordan en dramaturgia femenina actual. de 1986 a 2016, número 30 de la revista feminismo/s, que publica el instituto universitario de estudios de género de la universidad de alicante.

el volumen se compone de un bloque de artículos críticos sobre distintas autoras, obras y ejes temáticos, capítulo que complementa un segundo apartado con entrevistas a cuatro voces de la dramaturgia femenina actual: lola blasco, diana de paco, begoña tena y maría velasco.
en nuestro facebook les dejamos el link en pdf para descargar la revista. .
.
.
.

text:
i keep a lot of stuff bottled up, there’s a lot that i don’t share out loud. lately, i’ve been working through some trauma from events that happened well over 2 years ago. i guess, i just never wanted to talk about it before. because of this trauma, because of what happened to me, because of how this person treated me i spend a lot of time, without even realizing it, second guessing my self worth and if i even matter to those i care most about. i know no one is going to fully read this, but i guess what i’m trying to say is that trauma leaves a lasting impression without us even realizing it, that our brains end up thinking and acting differently because of the trauma, because of its lasting effect. i feel broken and inferior and i don’t like that. i feel like i’m a burden to my loved ones because the dumbest shit can trigger me. i just want to feel normal again. •
•
•
#trauma #metoo #depression #anxiety #selfharm #rapevictim #ptsd #workingthroughit #willprobablydelete

text:
#57 ciwit [3]
.
"ciwit yeuh ciwit (cubit nih cubit)," iseng si kakak pada adiknya. si adik yang menurut perkiraan saya berumur 3 tahun hanya bisa menepis. sesekali dia paksa kakaknya mundur. tapi si kakak tak mudah menyerah, tubuhnya yang sedikit lebih besar terus berupaya.
.
bersama si ibu, mereka menumpang kereta dari manggarai menuju selatan. bersebelahan duduk dengan saya semalam. si ibu berdiri di depan kami. tak banyak menggubris keisengan si anak. hanya diam, kosong, menatap jendela.
.
si adik perempuan tersenyum kecut, mulai kesal. dia malah memeluk kakaknya. "manis sekali," batin saya. si kakak bermuka bulat dengan bisul di atas mata, jidat, dan ujung lengan mulai tenang. dia menunjuk luka koreng di dengkul sang adik. "perih teu (perih tidak)?". si adik menggeleng. luka si adik tidak hanya itu. saya perhatikan ada setidaknya 4 luka bekas bisul di kaki, betis, dan paha. semua masih basah.
.
dari mana mereka? menuju pulang kah? mengapa si ibu membawa banyak barang? belanjaan atau...?
.
"umi, bapa ka mana (ibu, bapak ke mana)?", tetiba si adik melontarkan tanya di tengah padatnya penumpang kereta. si adik menatap jendela dan orang-orang bersliweran di setiap stasiun perhentian.
.
"teu aya bapa, geus mangkat. bapa maneh gelo (tidak ada bapak, sudah pergi. bapak kamu gila)", jawab si ibu dengan benci yang begitu dalam.
.
"ada yang mau lihat upin - ipin? ini pegang hp aku. yuk nonton yuk." ingin saya memeluk mereka. mengajaknya bermain bersama aimaruna. sepanjang perjalanan mereka menikmati tontonan itu. sayang, saya harus turun di depok lama. tapi semoga itu sedikit membasuh luka.
.
"terima kasih", ucap ibu mereka. saya tersenyum sambil melihat wajah lelahnya.
.
semoga kisah di ujung sana tidak seburuk pikir saya. ada doa menyelip dalam batin agar mereka terus kuat bersama.[]
.
📷 poem by rupi kaur
#torianthology
#hearmetoo
#16daysofactivism
#16haktp

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate™ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

my smile for years hid the pain and suffering i carried. my childhood wasn't all bed of roses. my mother was abusive. somehow, i rose from it. then in 2011, after i watched my father pass away, i fell into a deep depression. my rock and my protector gone. one month after his passing my sister & her husband brutally beat me up. returning back to work from my injuries earlier than i was supposed to be, my supervisor & manager threatened and bullied me at work. i asked myself,"if i'm just here to be used and abused, why am i still living? is this my destiny?" i ended up with ptsd. i became submissive, suicidal and zero trust in people. i was broken both mentally and physically. 5 yrs later i started lifting weights. i started to trust my friends i met at the gym. not only they taught me how to be strong physically but mentally as well. i was starting to feel and look stronger day by day month by month. i got to test out my new found strength. a person i had met attacked me and wouldn't stop. at first i became submissive and took the abuse then eventually i snapped and punched the person three times and took off. days later, i realized i am strong enough to fight back! my hardwork in the gym and my new friends helped me achieve my goals and since i want more!!! more strength, more gains! people ask me why i lift weights? am i not worried i'll look like a guy? get bulky? ha! bring it on! lifting weights not only help me physically but mentally as well and if it wasn't for my strong friends behind me, i would still be that submissive broken person. today my smile is genuine happiness. i'm so proud of myself & the only pain i have is after an intensive workout lifting weights. 🙏

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

.
[extrait] j’ai rêvé d’une formation pour les femmes et ce rêve se réalise sous la forme la plus accessible qui soit : une formation en ligne !  semble essentiel de se réapproprier nos corps ! le mouvement #metoo a montré l’ampleur de la misogynie ambiante, les violences gynécologies et obstétricales, notamment lors des accouchements (épisiotomie sans aviser la femme, « point du mari », etc.), sont encore trop fréquentes. il me semble que l’avancée des droits des femmes passent par notre réappropriation de nos corps et pour cela nous devons en connaître le fonctionnement et ainsi sortir de l’infantilisation médicale qui perdure depuis que les femmes sages-les sorcières, ont été persécutés détruisant par la même une transmission de génération en génération. cette transmission me touche d’autant plus que je suis mère d’une petite fille et j’aimerais lui transmettre ce que je n’ai malheureusement pas reçu de ma mère. j’aspire à ce que les nouvelles générations de femmes aient accès à ce savoir et qu’ainsi, elles puissent prendre soin de leur terre intérieure.
le lien d'inscription est dans ma bio 😉

text:
happy friday peeps!
.
and more importantly, happy #wineoclock time.  you know what that means, yeap, it's time for this weeks episdoe of the wine o'clock show and this week we chat with one of australia's most versatile and much loved entertainers. from leading tv roles on home and away, house husbands, big sky, dead gorgeous and host of national prime time shows celebrity singing bee, wheel of fortune, national bingo night and countless other tv programs, to lead roles in the stage shows wicked, rent and shout! he is certainly a star of both stage and screen.
.
when he’s not dancing with the stars, he is entertaining on channel 9’s carols by candlelight.  that's right, @timcampbelltwit is on the couch.
.
this week is all about christmas as tim celebrates 10 years of singing at @channel9 's carols by candlelight. tim has performed at venues all over the australia, been on hit tv show, smash hit theatre productions, so we find out why the channel 9 carols by candlelight event unique.  what’s been the highlight of performing at the carols over the last 10 years and what’s been his favourite song to deliver?
.
we also chat about the big christmas tree debate - in what order do you decorate? is it lights, tinsel, balls and decorations?
.
tim also give's his opinion on whether the 74 year old christmas classic “baby it’s cold outside” be removed from our radio stations after an ohio radio station has stopped playing a classic 74-year-old christmas song because it offends proponents of the increasingly criticized #metoo movement.
.
tim also released a new album this year called electrifying 80’s, our favourite era, we find out which amazing 80's classic's made the album and why.
.
all this a so much more, this week on the wine o'clock show. link in bio
.

text:
introducing our closing plenary panelists at the #likho indian lgbtq media summit in mumbai on december 15, 2018 for the panel discussion - "beyond #metoo: creating an equal, diverse, inclusive & safe media workplace". the panelists are vinta nanda, parmesh shahani, apsara reddy and anuraadha tewari. the panel will be moderated by urmi chanda vaz. 
likho is an initiative of bombay dost and humsafar trust to promote fair and inclusive representation of the lgbtq community in indian media. the event this year is presented by blued.

hei tänään nähdään helsingin vaatepuussa rennolla meiningillä klo 15-19. illan aikana kolmen kiinnostavan yhteistyökumppanimme puheenvuoroa:

klo 16 suomen #metoo liikkeen keulahahmo ohjaaja @heidi.linden 
klo 17 @solpesulapalvelut viestintäpäällikkö taija paavola kertoo kuukausi sitten lanseeratusta yhteistyökuviosta
klo 18 @kierratyskeskus tervehdyksen tuo ympäristöasiantuntija anu hakala

joustavasti illan aikana myös tilan idearikkaan visualistimme @marianaheikkila puheenvuoroja: "kuinka syntyi vaatepuun sisustus". tilan tavarat on lähes kaikki hankittu pääkaupunkiseudun kierrätyskeskuksesta.

lisäksi koko illan vaatepuun vanhoista pesulahenkareista loiditaan joulukransseja @jkukkatalo floristi saija sitolahden avulla.

glögiä ja pipareita sekä koko vaatepuu helsingin henkilökuntapaikalla: maaret, anni, vilma, sari ja soile-maria sekä kuvaajamme sara.

nähdään pian! ps. myös normaalisti vaatteiden lainausta :) #vaatepuu #vaatepuuhelsinki #vaatelainaamo #kaupunkilaistenyhteinenvaatekaappi #kruununhaka #avajaiset #pikkujoulut #yhteistyö

.
.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company “weaponised” the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users’ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms – facebook, in particular – were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign’s lesser reported “weapons of mass destruction”. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone’s personality. a user’s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call “populist political signalling”. cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

das, was männer in pornos sich wünschen mit frauen zu erleben, scheint es selbst dort nicht zu geben.

gewünscht ist ein starker moment des loslassens, fallenlassens, wo man niemanden gefallen muss und völlig man selbst sein kann.

in dem schroffen nackten akt des porn meint man, das zu finden.

studien und interviews mit pornodarstellern zeichnen allerdings ein anderes bild:
die pornodarsteller und die zuschauer fühlen sich danach nicht "aufgebaut", sondern eher nach einem kurzen kick in tieferer unbefriedigtheit als zuvor.
innere leere, ausgelaugt sein, und in der schleife des betruges, wird ein nächster "akt" vollzogen.
doch das ersehnte stellt sich nicht ein.

das was man(n) sucht, existiert.

es lässt sich finden.

in der konstellation mit einem menschen, der dir etwas bedeutet und der dich tiefer kennt und berührt hat, kannst du gemeinsam etwas erleben, was es so nirgendwo anders gibt.

es gibt einen ort, der nur im echten begegnen mit respekt und würde ein geheimnis offenbart.
und dich nicht nur sexuelle schöne und ungeahnte tiefen erleben lässt.... echt sein. wahr sein. nackt sein. sich safe begegnen. nah sein. 
trau dich!!

text:
tra tutte le città straniere, firenze è divenuta certo quella che io preferisco. più ci vivi e più ti accorgi di amarla. vi è qualcosa di accogliente da farmi sentire a casa mia. (tchaikovsky) 
среди всех заграничных городов городом, который предпочитаю, стала, конечно же, флоренция. чем больше тут живешь, тем больше замечаешь, что ее любишь. в ней есть что-то гостеприимное, что позволяет чувствовать себя как дома. (чайковский)

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company “weaponised” the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users’ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms – facebook, in particular – were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign’s lesser reported “weapons of mass destruction”. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone’s personality. a user’s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call “populist political signalling”. cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most impoant, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
my experience during the filming of ghosthunter was certainly a journey...literally healing and slaying my childhood demons while being filmed was a strange but very supported journey. i feel so privileged that such amazing people were behind making the film and part of my lifes traumatic experiences are now helping others which helps me to feel like something positive has come from all the pain it still causes me today. as a survivor who suffers complex ptsd and learning about my condition, i wish to inspire others to never give up and that although our mental health gives us daily battles they never define who we are. be kind to yourself but mostly remember you are human and we humans are born to feel emotion pain etc. its ok not to be ok xoxoxox love and light xoxo p.s. for those who are curious please check out #ghosthunterthemovie xoxoxoxox 
sorry for so many more people i was unable to tag who helped make this possible xoxoxoxox

text:
reiterating the provisions in the indian penal code and the protection of children from sexual offences (pocso) act, the supreme court on 11th december, 2018 restrained the media from revealing the names and identities of victims of sexual assault, in any manner.

while delivering the judgment in an application relating to the protection of identity of survivors, the court said that the media cannot disclose the identity of the victims to the public in any manner. it was made clear that the restriction would apply to all kinds of media including press, electronic and social media.

the court also ordered that identity of rape victims, who have died or who are unsound of mind, should not be disclosed even if the parents of the victim consent to the same.
.

.
.

.
.

text:
shuuuu 🤫
i shared excitedly this evening with an old friend that i was writing a book. my book, my story & my journey. she went on to ask me what it was about. she does & has known me for years, thus knowing some of my past,... “regrets” & “mistakes”, & i went on to say....
“hmmm not quite sure yet, (cause i’m not) but it's about my life, what i've gone through, the lessons i’ve learned, the girls and their miracles and all that god through his faithfulness has done and continues to do...& she lovingly said, (i know just out of love and concern)….”
ooooh kerry...well how much of your past are you going to share? cause surely you can’t divulgeeverything...because...you know...that once it’s in print...it’s out there forever!”
gulp, swallow, sigh, re-group, re-think, evaluate….i actually did recently stop to ponder this reality & thought...am i ready to share all this with my precious & innocent girls...i mean in my mind i had long ago decided that all my past testimony/past failures and lessons, would be things  i would only share with them when they are much, much older….and they could still be,...but she was right... it’s all out there  in print, and people can judge and talk and scandal and, and, and, & i had to silence my mind & ♥️ because i realized that, i realized it was already out….(and there’s more still to come), but it was already out there, and…and what??!! i know that i am no longer “that” person...that i am a new creation in christ, i know how he sees me, values me, talks about me, loves me, see’s and looks at me as righteous, pure & holy...not because of anything that i have done, but all because of what christ has done for me...so why....why would i ever for one second fall back into staying silent?
to not sharing how he has radically transformed and changed me life….& i will not stay silent for a second longer, i will share the hard, the dark, the ugly, the “nitty-gritty” because for too long the “enemy” has tried to shut me up, keep me quiet, had me chase after other things and i am tired…the world is hungry to hear truth, that freedom would be spoken, be sung, be danced, be declared, and not for any other reason, but to bring him glory/praise

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
“real wellness require real rebellion”. this is the intention that leads my eight week online program.

a program that helps you create a definition of wellness by first breaking down the definitions of wellness we have been previously sold in our capitalist & consumer society.

think about it for a moment… where does your definition of wellness come from?

it is from your family? have you acculturated family traditions and customs that truly nourish you spirit? or has what you have been passed down keeping you locked and rooted in ancestral trauma and a family lineage of internalized body hatred and suppression of self? 
be honest with yourself. do you know real wellness from your family of origin.

maybe your definition of wellness has evolved since living with your family.

maybe you have sought out self help books and development programs to really find your strive of living well… but have your ever taken the time to think about who has written these books. probably the same majority of people who’s ideologies harmed your family of origin💑. the majority of self development books are written by white men. patriarchy and white supremacy run hard in this industry despite the main buyer of “wellness” or self help books being women. try and find self help or development books written by a person of colour, someone non-gender conforming, someone with a history of trauma, someone not able bodied… can you find a self help or self development book written by someone like you?🤷🏻‍♀️ with a lack of diversity included in the the “writings” of wellness can you really trust to base your definition of wellness here?

maybe you haven’t fallen for the celebrity coaching fads who use trendy and cute quotations that acculturate and misrepresent years of psychological research. 🎓
maybe you have learned wellness through the media. through #hypersexualized images of women and commodification of the body. the diet industry presents in each models body. this learning could have been consciously (weight watchers anyone🙋🏻‍♀️) or unconsciously (by watching the victoria secrets fashion show🖥). either way the message is the same, wellness has been equated to desirability. ⬇️

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.
